<p class="">    <h2>Key Challenges in the Digital Humans for Video Market</h2>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Technological Limitations:</strong> Despite advancements in AI and graphics, creating hyper-realistic digital humans is still challenging. Issues such as motion capture inaccuracies and rendering time can hinder production quality.        </li>        <li>            <strong>High Production Costs:</strong> The costs associated with developing digital humans, including software, hardware, and skilled personnel, can be prohibitively high. This presents a barrier for smaller producers and startups.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Integration with Existing Workflows:</strong> Adopting digital humans into traditional video production workflows can be convoluted. Resistance from creative teams accustomed to conventional methods poses additional challenges.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Ethical Concerns:</strong> The potential misuse of digital humans raises ethical questions, particularly concerning identity, privacy, and deepfakes. This can lead to regulatory scrutiny and damage to brand reputation.        </li>        <li>            <strong>User Acceptance:</strong> Viewers may exhibit skepticism towards digital humans, struggling to relate to them emotionally. Establishing credibility and a connection with audiences remains a significant hurdle.        </li>    </ul>    <h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Digital Humans for Video Market</h2>    <ul>        <li>            <strong>Advancements in AI Technology:</strong> Continuous improvements in machine learning and AI can enhance the realism and functionality of digital humans, making them more appealing for various applications, including entertainment and customer service.        </li>        <li>            <strong>Increased Demand for Content:</strong> The relentless growth of streaming services and digital platforms creates a surging demand for diverse content, ope